05560nam a22007095i 9780889205826DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20061988xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892058267 a10.51644/97808892058262doi  a(DE-B1597)667248  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHQ1154 7aSOC0100002bisacsh04a305.422300aGender Bias in Scholarship :bThe Pervasive Prejudice /ced. by Winnie Tomm, Gordon Hamilton. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©1988  a1 online resource (226 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tTable Of Contents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tDedication -- tIntroduction -- tSexism In Sociological Research -- tThe Treatment Of The Sexes In Psychological Research -- tReassessing Interpretive Strategies In Literary Criticism -- tWomen And Education: On Being Female In Male Places -- tGender Bias In Art Education -- tRe-Visions Of The Past -- tOn The Treatment Of The Sexes In Scientific Research -- tEpistemology And Women In Philosophy: Feminism Is A Humanism -- tWhere All The Ladders Start: A Feminist Perspective On Social Science -- tSubject Index -- tName Index -- tAlso published by Wilfrid Laurier University Press for The Calgary Institute for the Humanities0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis multi-disciplinary anthology is about hermeneutical issues pertaining to gender ideology in university scholarship. The authors provide, from their own discipline, an extensive examination of the issues raised in the Social Sciences and Humanities Research Council of Canada pamphlet, "On the Treatment of the Sexes in Research," by Margrit Eichler and Jeanne Lapointe (1985). Gender bias is described and evaluated in the light of possible alternative perspectives which would alter the content and shape of research, including women as subjects of research and as researchers. The authors underscore the importance of acknowledging underlying gender imagery in the selection, interpretation, and communication of research data. They explore the notion of research as a social construction which is strongly aligned with the socially constructed notion of male and dissociated from the socially constructed notion of female. The focus is on refraining research ideology to include both female- and male-constructed imagery. Contributors include Marlene Mackie (sociology), Carolyn Larsen (psychology), Estelle Dansereau (literary criticism), Gisele Thibault (education), Alice Mansell (art), Eliane Leslau Silverman (history), Yvonne Lefebvre (biochemistry), Petra von Morstein (philosophy), and Naomi Black (political science).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLearning and scholarshipvCongresses. 0aLearning and scholarshipxCongresses. 0aSexismvCongresses. 0aSexismxCongresses. 4aSocial Science: Gender Studies. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh1 aBlack, Naomi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDansereau, Estelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton, Gordon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton, Gordon, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLarsen, Carolyn C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLefebvre, Yvonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMackie, Marlene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMansell, Alice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorstein, Petra von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1